        id: "viscometer",
        name: "Viscosity Meter (Viscometer)",
        purpose: "To measure the **viscosity (thickness)** or **resistance to flow** of liquids. In the dairy industry, it is used to measure and control the texture and consistency of products like **cream, yogurt, melted cheese, condensed milk, and ice cream mix**. Viscosity is a critical parameter for product quality and 'mouthfeel'.",
        principle: "The most common type is the <strong>rotational viscometer (like a Brookfield viscometer)</strong>. It works on the principle that the viscosity of a liquid is related to the **drag force** it exerts on a rotating object. \n1.  A **spindle** (a metal rod of various shapes and sizes) is attached to the instrument's motor and immersed in the liquid sample.\n2.  The motor attempts to rotate the spindle at a **constant, known speed (RPM)**.\n3.  The more viscous the liquid, the more it will **resist** the spindle's rotation. \n4.  The amount of **torque (rotational force)** the motor has to apply to keep the spindle rotating at that fixed speed is measured by a precise spring and sensor. \nThis measured **torque is directly proportional to the viscosity of the liquid**. The instrument calculates the viscosity reading (usually in **centipoise, cP** or **Pascal-seconds, Pa·s**) from this torque value (based on spindle type and speed) and displays it.",
        imageHint: "rotational viscometer working principle",
